										<p class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person">
											<img alt='' src='http://www.seobythesea.com/wp-content/wphb-cache/gravatar/0a0/0a01022160e5b5c8644c62c5f4280975x60.jpg' srcset='http://www.seobythesea.com/wp-content/wphb-cache/gravatar/0a0/0a01022160e5b5c8644c62c5f4280975x120.jpg 2x' class='avatar avatar-60 photo' height='60' width='60' /><span itemprop="name"><a href="https://metroim.com/" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Jennifer L Metro</a></span> <span class="says">says</span> </p>
										<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2018-01-25T08:49:22+00:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="http://www.seobythesea.com/2018/01/google-use-latent-semantic-indexing/#comment-553872" class="comment-time-link" itemprop="url">01/25/2018 at 8:49 am</a></time></p> </header>
									<div class="comment-content" itemprop="text">
										<p>You are such a genius that my eyes began to bleed reading this.<br />
											I take it that this article is a discussion of semantics, so to speak. I get that LSI is a specific term coined b4 the web. As such it is NOT what we (SEO&#8217;s) mean when we refer to it.<br />
											I think that (SEO) people are using LSI to mean the &#8220;synonym substitutions&#8221; and the &#8220;Context terms&#8221; you mentioned in one of your reply&#8217;s.<br />
