										<p class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person">
											<img alt='' src='http://www.seobythesea.com/wp-content/wphb-cache/gravatar/830/83051606d16792aaa2e9fee631696efex60.jpg' srcset='http://www.seobythesea.com/wp-content/wphb-cache/gravatar/830/83051606d16792aaa2e9fee631696efex120.jpg 2x' class='avatar avatar-60 photo' height='60' width='60' /><span itemprop="name"><a href="http://www.seobythesea.com" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Bill Slawski</a></span> <span class="says">says</span> </p>
										<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2018-01-29T07:49:58+00:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="http://www.seobythesea.com/2018/01/google-use-latent-semantic-indexing/#comment-553931" class="comment-time-link" itemprop="url">01/29/2018 at 7:49 am</a></time></p> </header>
									<div class="comment-content" itemprop="text">
										<p>Hi Joyita,</p>
										<p>Google never said in anyway that they were using LSI technology. They have admitted the use of related words in Phrase-Based indexing and in Rankbrain; but neither of those use LSI &#8211; they use more modern technology. I have seen people who sell SEO training suggest that people should use LSI keywords to help with Rankbrain, but I really question how helpful that would be. Google has pointed out other approaches involving context terms and realted words and schemas and structured data that are better approaches. I would question anyone suggesting the use of LSI, a 30 year old technology to handle something like Rankbrain. Have them explain how that works.</p>
