										<p class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person">
											<img alt='' src='http://www.seobythesea.com/wp-content/wphb-cache/gravatar/830/83051606d16792aaa2e9fee631696efex60.jpg' srcset='http://www.seobythesea.com/wp-content/wphb-cache/gravatar/830/83051606d16792aaa2e9fee631696efex120.jpg 2x' class='avatar avatar-60 photo' height='60' width='60' /><span itemprop="name"><a href="http://www.seobythesea.com" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Bill Slawski</a></span> <span class="says">says</span> </p>
										<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2018-02-12T09:37:02+00:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="http://www.seobythesea.com/2018/01/google-use-latent-semantic-indexing/#comment-554242" class="comment-time-link" itemprop="url">02/12/2018 at 9:37 am</a></time></p> </header>
									<div class="comment-content" itemprop="text">
										<p>Hi Boss Digital,</p>
										<p>Reading through the LSI patent was interesting for me. I mentioned that I had read a number of articles from one of the inventors, Susan Dumais, and the work that she did on Microsoft&#8217;s search engine show that she knows a lot about search. The LSI patent does use an example of a number of books, and having seen that did put it into perspective for me that it just wasn&#8217;t built for something the size of the Web that changes as quickly as the Web does (with user generated content, and new pages and sites springing up everyday.)</p>
